Yeah. The reason I try to not do accents outside of the romeo in chickenman with his overbearing one is that I actually don't tend to like them in novels. My own general way of viewing how to do it proper is to be as light as possible with it and explain that the main character is doing their best to "translate" what they're saying. Otherwise you run into a lot of frequent writing BS with how accents work.
>Texan/southern draw is a thin line between being a parody of itself and a real accent
>German is always too thick or too thin
>French is rare and done alright usually, but they ham it up a lot more than they should
>Mexican turns into spanglish fast, which then has the southern draw issue
>Australia can't be done without it being a parody
>British should be a gentle thing, most books go too hard with it
>Chavvy british is just fucking ork speak
>Fuck Japan
